@gwerbin A few comments:
1. you can always test the preliminary implementation now (https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/4803),
2. it doesn't actually do anything that you can't do yourself (I think...) - it does a bit of auto-generation of Cython code but it's all code that a user could write. The main reason to do it in Cython that the Numpy interface is pretty confusing and that we can hide that from you

@gwerbin Check out my PR, go to this line (https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/c7ba0c83d7fa7c0db60742b117b9e0207493013f/Cython/Compiler/UFuncs.py#L156) and add `print(code.impl)` and that should show the generated utility code I hope.

Note that the one thing that doesn't work in multiple return types where one of the types is a PyObject. That's really a consequence of the syntax I've used than a fundamental block.

There's also a small amount of C utility code. Think that all could be written in Cython but isn't (mainly for convenience). I think you'd add `print(TempitaUtilityCode.load("UFuncConsts", "UFuncs_C.c", context=context).impl)` (near https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/c7ba0c83d7fa7c0db60742b117b9e0207493013f/Cython/Compiler/UFuncs.py#L230) to see that.
